rComments: i did worse in his class than with my harder courses. his voice is too monotone

He has assigned plenty of readings for the course that are at times hard to understand but his lectures provide a wonderful summary for those readings in a clear and concise way that if you have read before class things will start to make sense. This course is an easy A, as long as one attends all the lectures and tutorials.
teacherRatingTags: ['Lecture heavy', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Get ready to read']

rComments: Victor Barac is very kind and knowledgeable in his field, however I did find lectures to be rather slow and boring. That being said, he was very clear about what to study and tests and grading were fair. Ask questions to try and stay engaged, and don't miss lecture because his slides have none of the real information you need. Overall good prof!
teacherRatingTags: ['Caring', 'Clear grading criteria', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: I've always been good at anthropology, but this prof definitely ruined the experience for me. I passed with an okay grade, but not as good as it should've been. His TAs were horrible markers and it took him days sometimes WEEKS to respond to emails. He wasn't a bad lecturer and his classes were pretty straightforward.
teacherRatingTags: ['Lecture heavy', 'Get ready to read', 'Graded by few things']

rComments: I had him for ANT102 and hated it. He was very slow, monotone, boring. I could barely attend his lectures from how uninterested HE himself seemed. However, in ANT208 he was the opposite. Still monotone at times but super passionate about pop culture which was apparent in his lectures. Take his 2nd and 3rd year courses. Good prof for ANT208.
He taught the linguistic side of anthro but it was easy although he was boring. I didn't try too much and got a 4.0 so it's so easy to get a good grade. Read and you would be fine.

I hated this course with a passion. This prof seemed like a very nice guy but very boring, monotone, and uninteresting to listen to.  The textbook was also very uninteresting and boring. Never showed up to class or read the textbook but passed with an ok mark. Regret not credit/no crediting this course when i had the chance.

Took a very long time to get back grades. Took a long time to respond to e-mail. Not helpful. Class itself alright. Test are a lot of M/C questions and essays. I would not recommend this excuse for a prof to anyone.
Seriously, amazing professor and made the course be interesting. Down to earth which made the lectures go by quickly.

Seems like a very nice guy, but his lectures are boring and often off topic. You don't have to go to class to pass, if you just read the textbook, take notes on it, and study it, you should be fine. His exams are just essays, so it helps to have some ideas prepared in advance. I don't think I'd take one of his classes again.

Although his lectures were often very long and boring, it wasn't too bad. He keeps things simple and to the point. Monotone at times and soft spoken. His mid-term and final exams are usually essay questions. Again, his questions are straight to the point, not filled with useless and confusing sentences. Buy the book, attend lectures, the usual.

Not inspirational at all. Did not gain any deeper understanding of the subject. Found the professor to be lazy and unknowledgeable on the topic. Waste of my money. Nice guy but I felt lost and confused most of the time. You need the textbook for enlightenment. Please avoid.

i wasn't very interested in the idea of the course in the beginning but i really liked it eve though others who i know didn't like it as much. he gets a bit monotone but he explains everything and has a lot of examples. he's approachable. i would recommend this course.
Knows his stuff, the university ought to be hiring him full-time.
He is really nice and his final was pretty easy. But his lectures are so boring and he goes off topic very often

A LOT OF KNOWLEDGE, but very monotone barely replies to emails, extremely lazy administrator, however his tests are mostly always have repeated questions from the past. Focuses on a hand full of KEY topics and asks a lot of questions on them. Reading and Writing essays are keys to success. Your proficiency in each will determine your mark.

I took this course as an anthropology major and I needed this credit. While he is not bad compared to most of the other profs, his lectures can get really boring. The final exam was okay since he reused some of the same questions as his previous years. I did surprisingly good on the essay, and I'm a terrible essay writer!

You learn some interesting topics in this course. I took this course as an elective. However there are a lot of readings to do. The midterms and exams all depend on using the theory from the lectures and the examples from the readings. The essay was not bad. The lectures can sometimes get boring. I just wished he showed videos in his lectures.
this class is what first hooked me on anthro- now I'm majoring in it. I didn't really like the essay or get anything out of it but everything else was great! Interesting lectures and fair tests
awesome course, awesome prof. if you actually listen to him he got highly interesting stuff to tell but yeah, you first have to listen...and he looks like Al Pacino!
Most boring class ever... Barac knows his stuff but the way he teaches is just... boring. I actually fell asleep just in front of him.

Methodical professor, download is powerpoints and fill them in during lecture and your game. Doesn't refer to text much, but tutorials focus on it, get a good TA. Interesting text, helpful website, do the multiple choice and you're golden for the exam and midterm. Interesting subject matter, nice professor, good to talk to.

Overall the class wasnt hard if you studied for the tests.. The MCQs were a mixture of both the text and lectures.. Lectures are pretty important and the TUTs as well.. Make sure you really do well in the tuts. since the TAs are one doing all the marking ..! But this prof wasnt hard at all ..I did quiet good just by attending his lecs.

This Professor was very entertaining at first, and really loved Anthropology, which made the course so much better. But near the end of the course, I began to attend the class less and less, because his lectures slowly became more bland. The course is jam packed too, so if you're taking this, better be ready to study. His Multiple Choice is a kills

This course was a joke. It's a degree requirement for ant sci majors, even though it's a social science class. The worse part is he recycled his lectures from my first year!  His "Myth, Ritual and Religion" lecture was the EXACT SAME as the one he did in first year. It's basically ANT102 spread out over a whole year. Getting marks back takes 4ever.
very very very hard.  Tests are EXTREMELY detailed..know EVERYTHING!!!!! good teacher though.....I liked him until I saw my marks
Do-able as long as you go!
He's hot.
Exams were easy so long as you listened to what he told you to study. Lectures were often amusing.
Most boring course ever. STAY AWAY!!

The mid-term and final were fine as long as you studied his lectures and the case studies in the text.  The lectures were interesting.  As long as you showed up to class and did a bit of studying, you were guaranteed a decent mark.

a cheap teacher.. the exam was terrible. not just myself who thinks so. the m/c questions was really tricky and cheap. with lots of c) a and b, d) none of the above. and he asks lots of question that he never went through in class. READ THE CASE STUDIES! or there will be consequences. and worst of all...he's always talking about sex in class
Very good prof.  keeps class interesting
He was a fair marker, his lectures were interesting, the concepts he discussed were clear and consise...no complaints at all, I would take another course with him.

A horrible class with an even more horrible teacher!!  Reguritate, regurgitate, regurgitate!!  Learned nothing that I could not have learned on my own by reading the text.  Would not recommend this course or teacher to my worst enemy.
Good professor. Interesting lectures. If you do your readings on time, you will be fine.

I am a 4th year student at UTM who has had Dr. Barac for 3 courses; I think he's very by-the-book because he is still very young, and lacks the stereotypical air of wisdom that many UofT profs have. I felt his tests were very fair, and marks fair too. He is definitly a better prof in higher year courses than the intro ones.
NIce guy and all, but his teaching is weak and his courses repetitive
lazy, methods of evaluation do not test actual skills learned.  if you can avoid taking his class, i urge you to do so.

I've never had a prof before that used the same text he used in the prerequisite and then needed to be told that was what he did!  His tests were easy if you have read ALL of the readings.  Seriously, miss one and say goodbye to more than half of a percentage OR MORe of your final grade.  Miscommunication between him and his TAs. Study and memorize
HARD HARD HARD EXAM!!!! BUT GOOD CLASS
WORST PROFF EVER.We had 3 textbooks...and his tests were MCQ which tested us on petty details that u mihgt lookover otherwise...HATED this class..screwed my GPA nicely.

THIS PROF IS AMAZING! he is really fun to talk to, and his courses are really good. Aside from the fact that he is very learned, he teaches in a way that is engaging, funny and professional. Overall, great class.
sucks!!!!!!!
He looks like a thin version of Selvester Stalone. Very cute!  I love his class even though it is getting harder.
Okay I love Barac, he is a great guy. However, some of his lectures so deviate from what we are talking about and they go into rants which can be interesting but often times are just confusing!
Very funny guy - didn't fall asleep in his classes
HOT! but...very boring. slide shows are a plus because sometimes its hard to pay attention.
